SIMPLE: feed
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Feed
<hw>Feed</hw> <pr>(f⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fed</conjf> <pr>(f⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Feeding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>f⟦emac⟧dan</ets>, fr. <ets>f⟦omac⟧da</ets> food; akin to OS.
<ets>f⟦omac⟧dian</ets>, OFries. <ets>f⟦emac⟧da</ets>,
<ets>f⟦omac⟧da</ets>, D. <ets>voeden</ets>, OHG. <ets>fuottan</ets>,
Icel. <ets>f⟦ae⟧⟦edh⟧a</ets>, Sw. <ets>f⟦oum⟧da</ets>, Dan.
<ets>f⟦oum⟧de</ets>. ⟦root⟧75. See <er>Food</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To give food to; to supply with nourishment; to satisfy the
physical huger of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If thine enemy hunger, <qex>feed</qex> him.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. xii.
20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unreasonable creatures <qex>feed</qex> their young.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To satisfy; gratify or minister to, as any sense,
talent, taste, or desire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>feed</qex> fat the ancient grudge I bear him.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Feeding</qex> him with the hope of liberty.</q>
<rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fill the wants of; to supply with that which is
used or wasted; <as>as, springs <ex>feed</ex> ponds; the hopper
<ex>feeds</ex> the mill; to <ex>feed</ex> a furnace with
coal.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To nourish, in a general sense; to foster,
strengthen, develop, and guard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt <qex>feed</qex> my people Israel.</q> <rj><qau>2 Sam.
v. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mightiest powers by deepest calms are <qex>fed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>B. Cornwall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To graze; to cause to be cropped by feeding, as
herbage by cattle; <as>as, if grain is too forward in autumn,
<ex>feed</ex> it with sheep</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Once in three years <qex>feed</qex> your mowing lands.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To give for food, especially to animals; to furnish
for consumption; <as>as, to <ex>feed</ex> out turnips to the cows; to
<ex>feed</ex> water to a steam boiler.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To supply (the
material to be operated upon) to a machine; <as>as, to <ex>feed</ex>
paper to a printing press</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To produce
progressive operation upon or with (as in wood and metal working
machines, so that the work moves to the cutting tool, or the tool to the
work).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Feed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Feed
<hw>Feed</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take food; to
eat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her kid . . . which I afterwards killed because it would not
<qex>feed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>De Foe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To subject by eating; to satisfy the appetite; to
feed one's self (upon something); to prey; -- with <xex>on</xex> or
<xex>upon</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leaving thy trunk for crows to <qex>feed</qex> upon.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be nourished, strengthened, or satisfied, as if
by food.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He <xex>feeds</xex> upon the cooling shade.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To place cattle to feed; to pasture; to
graze.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If a man . . . shall put in his beast, and shall <qex>feed</qex>
in another man's field.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxii. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Feed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Feed
<hw>Feed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is
eaten; esp., food for beasts; fodder; pasture; hay; grain, ground or
whole; <as>as, the best <ex>feed</ex> for sheep</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A grazing or pasture ground.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An allowance of provender given to a horse, cow,
etc.; a meal; <as>as, a <ex>feed</ex> of corn or oats</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A meal, or the act of eating.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For such pleasure till that hour⟦br⟧
At <qex>feed</qex> or fountain never had I found.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The water supplied to steam boilers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The motion, or act,
of carrying forward the stuff to be operated upon, as cloth to the
needle in a sewing machine; or of producing progressive operation upon
any material or object in a machine, as, in a turning lathe, by moving
the cutting tool along or in the work.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The
supply of material to a machine, as water to a steam boiler, coal to a
furnace, or grain to a run of stones.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The
mechanism by which the action of feeding is produced; a feed
motion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Feed bag</b></col>, <cd>a nose bag containing feed for a
horse or mule.</cd> -- <col><b>Feed cloth</b></col>, <cd>an apron for
leading cotton, wool, or other fiber, into a machine, as for carding,
etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Feed door</b></col>, <cd>a door to a furnace, by
which to supply coal.</cd> -- <col><b>Feed head</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>A cistern for feeding water by gravity to a steam boiler.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <cd>An excess of metal above a mold,
which serves to render the casting more compact by its pressure; -- also
called a <altname>riser</altname>, <altname>deadhead</altname>, or
simply <altname>feed</altname> or <altname>head</altname></cd>
<au>Knight.</au> -- <col><b>Feed heater</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<fld>(Steam Engine)</fld> <cd>A vessel in which the feed water for the
boiler is heated, usually by exhaust steam.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A
boiler or kettle in which is heated food for stock.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Feed motion</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Feed
gear</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>the train of mechanism
that gives motion to the part that directly produces the feed in a
machine.</cd> -- <col><b>Feed pipe</b></col>, <cd>a pipe for supplying
the boiler of a steam engine, etc., with water.</cd> -- <col><b>Feed
pump</b></col>, <cd>a force pump for supplying water to a steam boiler,
etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Feed regulator</b></col>, <cd>a device for
graduating the operation of a feeder.</cd> <au>Knight.</au> --
<col><b>Feed screw</b></col>, <cd>in lathes, a long screw employed to
impart a regular motion to a tool rest or tool, or to the work.</cd> --
<col><b>Feed water</b></col>, <cd>water supplied to a steam boiler,
etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Feed wheel</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a kind
of feeder. See <er>Feeder</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 8.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>feedback</ent>⟦br⟧
